Usually, people flock to SANParks' nature reserves to take a break from the rat race. These parks are now empty due to the lockdown. But, this doesn't mean SANParks is sitting idle. It's handed out over 300 food parcels to needy families this weekend. #Day59ofLockdown MAHUMANI VILLAGE, Limpopo - Usually, people flock to SANParks' nature reserves to take a break from the rat race. These parks are now empty due to the lockdown. But this doesn't mean SANParks is sitting idle. READ: Limpopo centralises food distribution It's handed out over 300 food parcels to needy families this weekend. “We actually identified 7,500 vulnerable families in and around our parks," said Xola Mfeke. "So we're giving 300 parcels in this Mahumani villages today [Saturday] and as part of the 5,000 parcels we're giving to families just in and around the Kruger National Park. " READ: 58,000 households have received food parcels - Zulu SANParks has also supplied 16 water tanks to the Mahumani area close to the Kruger National Park. The community is very grateful for the help they've received. “The purpose is to actually touch the lives of the vulnerable, the indigent and the poor of the poorest," said Hosi Ak Mahumani-Nkomo, the Mahumani Traditional Authority's chief of staff. READ: Virus lockdown boosts South African virtual safari tours "For me and my community, this speaks volumes. ” Many national parks are situated in rural or poor communities, which often depend on the parks for an income. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.